re, England":"Frodesley, Shropshire, England","Oswestry, Morton Regis, Shropshire, England":"Oswestry, Shropshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1370–":"about 1370–Deceased","1370–Male":"1370–Deceased","1375–Female":"1375–Deceased","1389–1466":"1389–1466","1335–Male":"1335–Deceased","1340–Female":"1340–Deceased","about 1370":"about 1370","1335":"1335","1455":"1455","1466":"1466","1389":"1389","about 1369":"about 1369","1375":"1375","about 1389":"about 1389","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","Oswestry, Shropshire, England":"Oswestry, Shropshire, England","Frodesley, Shropshire, England":"Frodesley, Shropshire, England","Oswestry, Morton Regis, Shropshire, England":"Oswestry, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Salter","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name for an extractor or seller of salt (a precious commodity in medieval times), from Middle English <i>salter(e)</i> ‘producer or seller of salt’. There may have been some post-medieval confusion with   Souter  ; see also   Saltman  .","English: occupational name from Middle English <i>sautreour</i> ‘minstrel, player of the psaltery (a stringed musical instrument)’ (Old French <i>sautere</i> ‘psaltery’, Latin <i>psalterium</i>, Greek <i>psaltērion</i>, from <i>psallein</i> ‘to sound’). Compare   Rutter  .","German: northern variant of   Salzer  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Salois","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Andre, Fabien, Normand.","French: unexplained. This surname is very rare in France. Compare   Salter  ,   Saltus  , and   Salway  .","History: Claude Salois from Lille in Nord, France, married Anne Mabille in Quebec City, QC, <i>c.</i> 1666."]},{"name":"Salt","meanings":["English: habitational name from Salt (Staffordshire), from Old English <i>selte</i> ‘salt pit’. Occasionally the name may be a nickname for a producer or seller of salt, from Middle English <i>salt</i> ‘salt’ (compare   Salter  ), but evidence is lacking.","Native American (Navajo): from a translation into English of the name of the Navajo clan <i>Áshįįhi</i> ‘Salt People’."]},{"name":"Saulter","meanings":["English: variant of   Salter  ."]},{"name":"Saltman","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): occupational name for a producer or seller of salt, from Middle English <i>salt</i> ‘salt’ + <i>-man</i>. See also   Salter  .","Americanized form (translation into English) of German and Jewish (Ashkenazic)   Salzmann   or Jewish (Ashkenazic)   Saltsman  , or of their rare German cognate <b>Saltmann</b>."]},{"name":"Souter","meanings":["English: occupational name from Middle English <i>souter(e)</i>, <i>suter(e)</i> ‘shoemaker, cobbler’ (Old English <i>sūtere</i>, from Latin <i>sūtor</i>, an agent derivative of <i>suere</i> ‘to sew’). In early Modern English, pronunciation of the name would regularly develop from /su:ter/ to /sautə(r)/ (rhyming with <i>outer</i>), or to /sutə(r)/, as in   Sutter  . In Scots, however, it remained unchanged, with the spelling <i>-ou-</i> representing /u/. In parts of southern England it seems also to have remained as /u:/; see   Suter   (2).","Americanized form of German   Sauter  , a cognate of 1 above.","Flemish (<b>De Souter</b>): occupational name for a producer or seller of salt, from an agent derivative of Middle Dutch <i>sout</i> ‘salt’."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":12,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":85,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard John Salter was born about 1370, in Oswestry, Shropshire, England, his father, John Salter, was 37 and his mother, Anne Kiffen, was 32. He married Gwensi Salter about 1389, in Oswestry, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"about 1370–":"umbes 1370–Surnud","1370–Male":"1370–Surnud","1375–Female":"1375–Surnud","1389–1466":"1389–1466","1335–Male":"1335–Surnud","1340–Female":"1340–Surnud","about 1370":"umbes 1370","1335":"1335","1455":"1455","1466":"1466","1389":"1389","about 1369":"umbes 1369","1375":"1375","about 1389":"umbes 1389","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","Oswestry, Shropshire, England":"Oswestry, Shropshire, England","Frodesley, Shropshire, England":"Frodesley, Shropshire, England","Oswestry, Morton Regis, Shropshire, England":"Oswestry, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1370–":"noin 1370–Kuollut","1370–Male":"1370–Kuollut","1375–Female":"1375–Kuollut","1389–1466":"1389–1466","1335–Male":"1335–Kuollut","1340–Female":"1340–Kuollut","about 1370":"noin 1370","1335":"1335","1455":"1455","1466":"1466","1389":"1389","about 1369":"noin 1369","1375":"1375","about 1389":"noin 1389","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","Oswestry, Shropshire, England":"Oswestry, Shropshire, England","Frodesley, Shropshire, England":"Frodesley, Shropshire, England","Oswestry, Morton Regis, Shropshire, England":"Oswestry, Shropshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1370–":"environ 1370–Décédé","1370–Male":"1370–Décédé","1375–Female":"1375–Décédée","1389–1466":"1389–1466","1335–Male":"1335–Décédé","1340–Female":"1340–Décédée","about 1370":"environ 1370","1335":"1335","1455":"1455","1466":"1466","1389":"1389","about 1369":"environ 1369","1375":"1375","about 1389":"environ 1389","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","Oswestry, Shropshire, E